{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Add execution-phase plan reviews\n\n## Goal\nAllow plan changes made during implementation to be reviewed with a fixed 0.80 blocking floor, while preserving stricter planning reviews and preventing a signature from binding phase or related material that changed during review.\n\n## Implementation\n- Add reducer-maintained `plan_review_phase: planning|execution` to compiled state, distinct from prompt `execution_mode`. Only the winning/normal `process_status` branch updates it: a committed winning STATUS target `in_progress` sets execution; target `open` sets planning; every other target preserves the current value. Losing fork events never update it, and force transitions use the same winning target rule. Carry the field through SNAPSHOT compaction. Verify `_snapshot_strip_keys()` in `_commands/compact.py` does not strip it. Review reads the compiled field O(1), never scans raw history.\n- For a pre-feature snapshot without the field, bootstrap planning when compiled status is `open` or `idea`, execution for every other known status. An unknown status raises the existing reducer validation error rather than guessing. Bump `reducer/_cache.py::_REDUCER_CACHE_VERSION` so the first post-upgrade reduction applies this once; later snapshots persist it. Emit one structured INFO `plan_review_phase_bootstrap` with ticket ID, compiled status, and chosen phase. This is a cache recomputation, not a write/compaction wave: ordinary reads rebuild the local derived cache lazily and do not append ticket events.\n- Restructure `build_manifest`'s fixed initial list to emit exact lines in this order after `advisory:` and before `rebar-version:`: `review-phase: planning|execution`, then for execution only `priority-floor: 0.80`. Each line has exactly a prefix, one ASCII space, and one token. Add `manifest.validate_review_phase_metadata(phase: object, floor: object, *, legacy_absent: bool) -> ReviewPhaseMetadata` as the single grammar/policy helper; `ReviewPhaseMetadata` is exactly `{phase: planning|execution, priority_floor: float|None}`. Manifest parsers extract raw tokens and call it. `manifest_review_phase()` returns legacy planning only when the line is absent; `manifest_priority_floor()` returns `None` only when absent. The helper raises `ManifestFormatError` for duplicates signaled by callers, missing/extra tokens, unknown phase, bool/non-numeric/non-finite floor, or floor outside `[0.0, 1.0]`; a floor without a phase and execution without exactly one floor are malformed. Existing parsers scan by prefix rather than fixed offsets, so added lines do not change regver/material/dependency parsing. The signed line records the phase the LLM ran under; compiled state records current phase, and compatibility compares these distinct values rather than comparing current state to itself.\n- Extend 75de's `DerivedPlanReviewHealth` with always-present `phase_status: compatible|incompatible|malformed`. Compatibility table: current planning + signed planning/legacy planning = compatible; current planning + signed execution = incompatible; current execution + signed planning/legacy planning = compatible; current execution + signed execution floor >= 0.80 = compatible; any malformed phase/floor or execution floor < 0.80 = malformed/incompatible respectively (`malformed` is syntax/shape only, `incompatible` is syntactically valid policy mismatch). The fixed 0.80 protocol policy is not configurable. Raising it later invalidates lower-floor execution attestations; lowering it accepts higher-floor attestations without migration.\n- Extend 75de's `compute_validity` plan-review branch to parse phase/floor with pins after signature/kind verification and return phase_status on every later result. After prerequisite 75de is implemented on the feature branch, claim, idempotent reuse, and drift refresh share `compute_validity(DEFAULT|DRIFT_REFRESH)` and inherit phase enforcement. Child 2bbd's later CLOSE call inherits it. Child cb6b's later audit/UI health reads the same result. Completion-verifier calls never invoke phase, floor, or pin parsers.\n- Persist review-time phase data for failed-sign recovery with an exact additive `plan_review_result_v2` schema: new full reviews always write JSON `review_phase` as lowercase string `planning` or `execution`; planning omits `priority_floor`; execution writes JSON number `priority_floor: 0.8` (not string and not null). For legacy sidecars, both keys absent means planning/None. A present null, only-one-key legacy combination, bool, string floor, unknown phase, planning with a floor, or execution without a floor is malformed. Add `sidecar.parse_review_phase_metadata(payload) -> ReviewPhaseMetadata`; it passes raw JSON values to `manifest.validate_review_phase_metadata` and translates `ManifestFormatError` to `SidecarReviewPhaseError`. `resign_plan_review` calls this named parser, compares the result with current compiled phase, and refuses incompatible/malformed re-sign. A passing re-sign builds the manifest from the recorded review-time phase/floor, not a newly inferred phase. This edit composes after 75de's related-material sidecar guard and before acaf's current pin collection/sign step.\n- Thread phase through every Pass-3 entry. Add required `review_phase` with string enum `planning|execution` to both closed schemas `plan_review_precheck_output.schema.json` and `plan_review_decide_input.schema.json`, updating their `properties` and `required` arrays atomically. `workflow_ops.plan_review_precheck` emits the compiled value. In `llm/workflow/gates/plan-review.yaml`, add `review_phase: ${{ steps.precheck.outputs.review_phase }}` to both `plan_review_decide` `with:` blocks: the code-grounded verify branch and the non-agentic else branch. `plan_review_decide` requires the field and calls `orchestrator.pass3_over_findings(..., execution_review=(review_phase == \"execution\"))`. The verify-failure recovery in `workflow/gate_dispatch.py` reads `precheck[\"review_phase\"]` and passes the same bool; absence in a legacy persisted run defaults planning. These are the complete call sites: normal workflow calls pass the explicit bool; direct unit/legacy callers may use the default false only when they intentionally model planning. The schema/YAML/code ship atomically from one checkout; workflows are synchronous and have no cross-version in-flight server state. Update schema golden/cutover tests for the closed output contract and rollback together.\n- Define `orchestrator.pass3_over_findings(findings, verifs, *, execution_review: bool = False)` exactly at the module-level function. Its local `_threshold_for` closure lexically captures the parameter, calls `_criteria.threshold_for(...)`, destructures `(block_threshold, blocking_enabled)`, and returns `(max(block_threshold, 0.80), blocking_enabled)` only when `execution_review and blocking_enabled`; otherwise it returns the original pair. Pass this closure to `review_kernel.pass3_over_findings`. This changes normal Pass-3 only: advisory-only criteria keep `blocking_enabled=False`, novelty and completion floors are untouched, deterministic structural failures remain blocking, and sub-floor findings remain visible.\n- Own one pre-sign generation transaction for ordinary review, drift refresh, and re-sign. `PlanReviewGeneration` is `{phase, priority_floor, own_material, relation_snapshot, ticket_store_revision}` where `relation_snapshot` is child acaf's exact `PlanRelationSnapshot` and equality is dataclass equality across every field. Full review collects the initial generation before the LLM; drift refresh and re-sign collect it immediately before their non-LLM probe. No ticket-store write occurs before the model/probe succeeds, so an LLM/provider failure retains existing unsigned INDETERMINATE behavior and leaves no partial state.\n- Before signing, retain one immutable `initial_generation` captured before the LLM/probe; retries never replace this baseline. Retry outside the lock at most three times only for an unstable tracker revision: read clean tracker HEAD, collect a fresh generation, read HEAD again; unequal HEADs emit structured WARN `plan_review_generation_retry` with attempt/before/after and retry. A stable fresh generation unequal to the initial generation is terminal unsigned stale (`plan_review_generation_changed`) and requires re-review; it is not retried. Under the global write lock, require the same clean HEAD and exact generation, then append and commit the signature atomically. Under-lock HEAD/generation mismatch consumes a retry; exhaustion returns retryable unsigned. `LockTimeout` returns retryable unsigned without writing. Dirty/unmerged tracker or other terminal collection/sign failure emits structured ERROR `plan_review_sign_aborted` and returns unsigned without traceback.\n- Document the phase/floor manifest contract, health compatibility table, fixed-floor rationale, generation transaction, and rollback behavior in advanced `docs/plan-review-gate.md`. Rollback disables claim/close enforcement first; old reducers preserve the unknown snapshot field during re-compaction. If old code fully re-reduces raw events after its own cache bump, the phase field is absent and a later forward upgrade reboots it from compiled status; operators accept that documented loss of historical phase precision during the rollback window.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Winning entry into `in_progress` sets compiled `plan_review_phase=execution`.\n- [ ] Winning entry into `open` sets compiled `plan_review_phase=planning`.\n- [ ] Other winning status targets preserve the projection.\n- [ ] Losing fork STATUS events never update the projection.\n- [ ] Force transitions follow the same winning target rule.\n- [ ] Normal SNAPSHOT compaction and older-reducer snapshot pass-through preserve the exact field value.\n- [ ] The rollback test proves old-code raw-event re-reduction drops the unknown field and forward upgrade reboots it from compiled status, with the documented precision-loss window.\n- [ ] Pre-feature open/idea snapshots bootstrap planning once; every other known status bootstraps execution once.\n- [ ] Bootstrap emits the exact structured INFO and does not append ticket events.\n- [ ] Reducer-cache versioning activates the lazy bootstrap idempotently.\n- [ ] Planning manifests contain exactly `review-phase: planning` in the documented position.\n- [ ] Execution manifests contain exactly `review-phase: execution` then `priority-floor: 0.80` in the documented position.\n- [ ] Legacy phase-less attestations parse as planning.\n- [ ] Every named phase/floor syntax error raises `ManifestFormatError`; existing manifest parsers remain unchanged.\n- [ ] Planning state accepts planning/legacy and rejects syntactically valid execution attestations.\n- [ ] Execution state accepts planning/legacy and execution floor >= 0.80.\n- [ ] Execution state rejects a syntactically valid execution floor < 0.80 as incompatible.\n- [ ] Malformed phase/floor produces `phase_status=malformed`.\n- [ ] `DerivedPlanReviewHealth.phase_status` is present on every plan-review validity result.\n- [ ] Claim, reuse, drift refresh, and re-sign enforce phase through the shared validity/phase helpers; child 2bbd and cb6b consume the same boundary later.\n- [ ] Completion-verifier validity never calls phase, floor, or pin parsers.\n- [ ] Re-sign parses the exact v2 JSON phase fields through `sidecar.parse_review_phase_metadata`, uses the recorded values, and refuses every incompatible/malformed variant.\n- [ ] Execution Pass-3 destructures `(block_threshold, blocking_enabled)` and floors only the float threshold when blocking is enabled.\n- [ ] A production workflow integration test starts from compiled execution phase and proves both YAML decide branches receive `review_phase` and block a finding below 0.80 that planning would not block.\n- [ ] The verify-failure recovery test proves `gate_dispatch` passes execution phase to Pass-3 and legacy missing phase defaults planning.\n- [ ] Closed-schema golden tests prove `review_phase` is required in both declared schemas and schema/YAML/code rollback is version-coherent.\n- [ ] Planning Pass-3 returns the original threshold pair unchanged.\n- [ ] Advisory-only criteria, novelty/completion floors, deterministic failures, and visible sub-floor findings retain their documented behavior.\n- [ ] A stable generation equal to the initial generation signs and commits under one lock.\n- [ ] Any stable phase, own-material, relationship, related-fingerprint, or generation-field change returns terminal unsigned stale.\n- [ ] HEAD instability retries at most three times with exact WARN fields, then returns retryable unsigned.\n- [ ] Under-lock mismatch retries; `LockTimeout` returns retryable unsigned; neither writes a signature.\n- [ ] Dirty/unmerged or terminal signing failure returns unsigned and emits `plan_review_sign_aborted`.\n- [ ] Model/provider failure before signing writes no ticket event or signature and retains existing unsigned INDETERMINATE behavior.\n- [ ] The production-path integration test covers stable collection, under-lock HEAD re-verification, signature append, and commit end to end.\n- [ ] `docs/plan-review-gate.md` contains sections for the phase/floor manifest contract, phase_status compatibility table, fixed-0.80 rationale, PlanReviewGeneration transaction, and rollback precision-loss behavior.\n\n## Verification\n- `pytest -q tests/unit/test_plan_review_phase_reducer.py tests/unit/test_plan_review_phase_manifest.py` proves lifecycle projection, bootstrap, compaction, grammar, ordering, and parser compatibility.\n- `pytest -q tests/unit/test_plan_review_phase_validity.py tests/unit/test_plan_review_execution_floor.py tests/unit/test_plan_review_resign.py` proves the compatibility table, every consumer seam, tuple-aware threshold wrapping, completion isolation, and sidecar recovery.\n- `pytest -q tests/unit/test_plan_review_sign_transaction.py` proves stable/change/retry/exhaustion/dirty/LockTimeout/logging and no-write failure paths.\n- `pytest -q tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_plan_review_sign_transaction.py tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_plan_review_execution_floor.py tests/interfaces/contracts/test_workflow_schema_golden.py` runs production signing, both automatic execution-floor branches, verify-failure recovery, and closed-schema contract checks.\n- `pytest -q tests/unit/test_plan_review_docs.py` verifies the five required advanced-documentation sections.\n- Run `make check` and the full non-LLM test suite, including the named integration and rollback tests.\n"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784554673674473001,"uuid":"af4c7c01-9f69-4481-8e3f-0208ed65107b"}